Maven Plugins
What are Maven Plugins?

In Apache Maven, plugins are the core components that perform tasks during the build lifecycle. Maven itself is lightweight, and almost every action is executed through plugins.

Examples of tasks handled by plugins:

Compiling Java code
Running tests
Packaging JAR/WAR files
Generating documentation
Deploying applications
Managing dependencies
Why Maven Plugins are Important

Without plugins, Maven cannot:

Compile source code
Execute unit tests
Package applications
Generate reports
Deploy artifacts

Plugins make Maven:

Extensible
Reusable
Standardized
Automated
Types of Maven Plugins
1. Core Plugins

These are officially maintained by the Maven team and commonly used.

Examples:

Plugin	Purpose
maven-compiler-plugin	Compiles Java source code
maven-surefire-plugin	Runs unit tests
maven-jar-plugin	Creates JAR files
maven-war-plugin	Creates WAR files
maven-clean-plugin	Cleans build directories
maven-install-plugin	Installs artifact into local repository
maven-deploy-plugin	Deploys artifact to remote repository
2. Reporting Plugins

Used for generating reports and project documentation.

Examples:

maven-javadoc-plugin
maven-site-plugin
maven-project-info-reports-plugin
Plugin Goals

Each plugin contains one or more goals.

Example:

compiler:compile
clean:clean
surefire:test

Syntax:

mvn plugin-name:goal

Example:

mvn clean:clean
mvn compiler:compile
Plugin Configuration in pom.xml

Plugins are configured inside the <build> section.

Example:

<build>
    <plugins>

        <plugin>
            <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
            <artifactId>maven-compiler-plugin</artifactId>
            <version>3.11.0</version>

            <configuration>
                <source>17</source>
                <target>17</target>
            </configuration>
        </plugin>

    </plugins>
</build>
Common Maven Plugins
1. Maven Compiler Plugin

Used to compile Java source code.

Example:

<plugin>
    <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
    <artifactId>maven-compiler-plugin</artifactId>
    <version>3.11.0</version>

    <configuration>
        <source>17</source>
        <target>17</target>
    </configuration>
</plugin>

Command:

mvn compile
2. Maven Surefire Plugin

Used for running unit tests.

Example:

<plugin>
    <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
    <artifactId>maven-surefire-plugin</artifactId>
    <version>3.2.5</version>
</plugin>

Command:

mvn test
3. Maven JAR Plugin

Creates executable or normal JAR files.

Example:

<plugin>
    <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
    <artifactId>maven-jar-plugin</artifactId>
    <version>3.4.1</version>
</plugin>

Command:

mvn package
4. Maven WAR Plugin

Used for packaging web applications.

Example:

<plugin>
    <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
    <artifactId>maven-war-plugin</artifactId>
    <version>3.4.0</version>
</plugin>
5. Maven Clean Plugin

Deletes target folder and previous build files.

Example:

<plugin>
    <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
    <artifactId>maven-clean-plugin</artifactId>
    <version>3.3.2</version>
</plugin>

Command:

mvn clean
Maven Build Lifecycle and Plugins

Plugins are attached to lifecycle phases.

Lifecycle Phase	Plugin Goal
compile	compiler:compile
test	surefire:test
package	jar:jar
install	install:install
deploy	deploy:deploy
Executing Plugins
Direct Execution
mvn compiler:compile
Lifecycle Execution
mvn package

This automatically runs:

compile
test
package
Custom Plugin Configuration Example
<plugin>
    <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
    <artifactId>maven-surefire-plugin</artifactId>
    <version>3.2.5</version>

    <configuration>
        <skipTests>true</skipTests>
    </configuration>
</plugin>

Command:

mvn test

Result:

Tests are skipped.
Plugin Management

Used to define plugin versions centrally.

Example:

<build>
    <pluginManagement>
        <plugins>

            <plugin>
                <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
                <artifactId>maven-compiler-plugin</artifactId>
                <version>3.11.0</version>
            </plugin>

        </plugins>
    </pluginManagement>
</build>
Advantages of Maven Plugins
Automation of build tasks
Standard project structure
Easy dependency integration
Reusable configurations
Improved CI/CD support
Better project consistency
Real-Time Example

Suppose you build a Spring Boot application:

Compiler plugin compiles code
Surefire plugin runs tests
JAR plugin packages application
Deploy plugin uploads artifact to repository

Single command:

mvn clean install
Interview Questions
Q1. What is a Maven Plugin?

A plugin is a reusable component that performs specific build tasks in Maven.

Q2. Difference between Dependency and Plugin?
Dependency	Plugin
Used in application code	Used during build process
Added inside <dependencies>	Added inside <plugins>
Provides libraries	Provides build functionality
Q3. What is a Goal in Maven?

A goal is a specific task executed by a plugin.

Example:

compiler:compile
Q4. What is Plugin Management?

It centralizes plugin versions and configurations for child projects.

Summary
Maven plugins perform build tasks.
Plugins contain goals.
Plugins are configured in pom.xml.
Maven lifecycle phases trigger plugin goals automatically.
Common plugins include compiler, surefire, clean, jar, and war plugins.



Introduction to Gradle
What is Gradle?

Gradle is an open-source build automation and dependency management tool used mainly for:

Java projects
Spring Boot applications
Android applications
Kotlin and Groovy projects

Gradle combines the best features of:

Maven (dependency management)
Ant (flexibility)

It is designed to provide:

Faster builds
Flexible configurations
Better performance
Features of Gradle
Incremental builds
Dependency management
Plugin support
Multi-project builds
Faster execution using build caching
Flexible scripting
Supports Java, Kotlin, Groovy, Android, C++, etc.
Why Use Gradle?

Gradle is popular because:

Builds are faster than Maven
Configuration is less verbose
Highly customizable
Preferred for Android development
Better performance in large projects
Gradle Build Script

Gradle uses:

build.gradle (Groovy DSL)
OR
build.gradle.kts (Kotlin DSL)

Example:

plugins {
    id 'java'
}

group = 'com.example'
version = '1.0'

repositories {
    mavenCentral()
}

dependencies {
    testImplementation 'org.junit.jupiter:junit-jupiter:5.10.0'
}

test {
    useJUnitPlatform()
}
Important Gradle Concepts
1. Project

A Gradle project can be:

Single project
Multi-module project
2. Task

Task is the basic execution unit in Gradle.

Examples:

compileJava
test
build
clean

Run task:

gradle build
3. Dependency Management

Dependencies are added inside:

dependencies {
}

Example:

implementation 'org.springframework.boot:spring-boot-starter-web'
Gradle Build Lifecycle

Gradle has 3 phases:

Phase	Description
Initialization	Identifies project/modules
Configuration	Configures tasks
Execution	Executes selected tasks
Common Gradle Commands
Command	Purpose
gradle build	Complete build
gradle clean	Removes build files
gradle test	Runs tests
gradle run	Runs application
gradle tasks	Lists tasks
gradle dependencies	Displays dependencies
Gradle Plugins

Plugins add additional features.

Example:

plugins {
    id 'java'
    id 'application'
}

Popular plugins:

Java plugin
Spring Boot plugin
Application plugin
WAR plugin
Advantages of Gradle
Faster builds using incremental compilation
Less XML configuration
Flexible scripting
Excellent for large projects
Preferred for Android development
Supports parallel execution
Disadvantages of Gradle
Steeper learning curve
Complex scripts can become difficult
Less standardized than Maven
Debugging build scripts may be harder
Maven vs Gradle
Feature	Maven	Gradle
Build Script	XML (pom.xml)	Groovy/Kotlin DSL
Performance	Slower	Faster
Flexibility	Limited	Highly flexible
Learning Curve	Easier	Moderate
Configuration	Verbose	Concise
Dependency Management	Excellent	Excellent
Build Speed	Moderate	Faster with caching
Convention	Strict conventions	Flexible conventions
Android Support	Limited	Official Android build tool
Multi-project Support	Good	Excellent
Customization	Moderate	Very high
Example Comparison
Maven Dependency
<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-web</artifactId>
</dependency>
Gradle Dependency
implementation 'org.springframework.boot:spring-boot-starter-web'

Gradle configuration is shorter and easier to read.

When to Use Maven?

Use Maven when:

Team prefers standardization
Project is medium-sized
Simpler configuration is needed
Beginners are involved
When to Use Gradle?

Use Gradle when:

Build performance matters
Project is large and complex
Android development is involved
Advanced customization is needed
Interview Questions
Q1. What is Gradle?

Gradle is an open-source build automation tool used for compiling, testing, packaging, and managing dependencies.

Q2. Why is Gradle faster than Maven?

Gradle supports:

Incremental builds
Build caching
